I. PURPOSE AND BILL SUMMARY
On February 10, 2025, Rep. Finstad, along with Rep. Hageman,
Rep. Moran, Rep. Salazar, Rep. Meuser, Rep. Nunn, Rep. Steil, and
Rep. Stauber, introduced H.R. 1163, the Prove It Act of 2025. H.R.
1163 strengthens the Regulatory Flexibility Act (RFA) by requiring
federal agencies to thoroughly assess the direct and indirect im-
pacts of regulations on small businesses and to publicly share up-
dates and reviews of final rules. The bill also allows small busi-
nesses to challenge agency actions through the SBA’s Office of Ad-
vocacy when agencies fail to meet these requirements.
II. NEED FOR LEGISLATION
On May 22, 2024, the Committee released a report titled ‘‘Regu-
latory Flexibility Act (RFA) Report: Agencies’ Noncompliance with
the RFA.’’ The report was a result of a 15-month long investigation
in which the Committee found that agencies frequently failed to
properly assess the true impact of their rules on small businesses,
among other agency efforts to skirt RFA requirements.
This bill codifies efforts ordered under President Trump’s Execu-
tive Order 14192 ‘‘Unleashing Prosperity Through Deregulation.’’1
H.R. 1163 is necessary to address longstanding deficiencies in
agency compliance with the RFA. The RFA requires ‘‘federal agen-
cies to consider the effects of their regulations on small businesses
and other small entities.’’ Unfortunately, agencies are not properly
considering the effects of their regulations on small businesses.
Congress has not amended the RFA since 2010, therefore it is es-
sential for H.R. 1163 to strengthen procedural safeguards and shift
power back to small businesses. The RFA was a pivotal first step
in ensuring that small businesses have a way to challenge the over-
ly burdensome administrative state, but agencies still underreport,
minimize or ignore the effect regulations have on small businesses.
The Prove It Act of 2025 will help force the administrative state to
comply with the RFA, ensure indirect costs on small businesses are
properly accounted for, and gives small businesses a way to chal-
lenge non-compliant agencies.
III. HEARINGS
On April 1, 2025, the Committee on Small Business held a hear-
ing examining matters related to H.R. 1163 entitled ‘‘The Golden
Age: Unleashing Main Street Through Deregulation.’’
IV. COMMITTEE CONSIDERATION
The Committee on Small Business met in open session, with a
quorum being present, on April 30, 2025, and ordered H.R. 1163,
as amended, to be reported favorably to the House of Representa-
tives by a roll call vote of 15 ayes to 11 nos. During the markup
five amendments were offered.
