VI. SECTION-BY-SECTION OF H.R. 1163
Section 1—Short title
This act may be cited as the ‘‘Prove It Act of 2025.’’
Section 2—Initial Regulatory Flexibility Analysis
This section requires agencies to consider ‘‘indirect costs’’ when
conducting an RFA certification. This includes costs to small enti-
ties which purchase from or sell to directly impacted entities, are
regulated by other government entities because of the rule, or are
subject to other regulations because of the rule.
Any small entity or group representing small entities can peti-
tion the SBA Office of Advocacy (Advocacy) to review an agency’s
certification.
• Advocacy will conduct an initial review. If the rule does
not have a significant economic impact on a substantial num-
ber of small entities, the review stops there. If it does, Advo-
cacy has 10 days to notify the petitioner and agency that Advo-
cacy will do a full review.
• The full review must consider whether the agency: (1) cor-
rectly considered which small entities would be impacted; and
(2) accurately and wholly considered the relevant economic
data and impact.
• Advocacy must host a meeting between itself, the peti-
tioner, representatives of the agency, and the Administrator of
the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA)
» This meeting allows each side to defend its position
and Advocacy to ask questions.
• Final review must be published by Advocacy within 30
days.
• If determined to have a substantial economic impact on a
significant number of small entities, the agency that promul-
gated the proposed rule must perform an Initial Regulatory
Flexibility Analysis (IRFA) and Final Regulatory Flexibility
Analysis (FRFA) for the rule.
• If the agency fails to comply with any of the above, the
rule does not apply to small entities.
Section 3—Publication of guidance
For any rule determined to have a significant economic impact
on a substantial number of small entities, the promulgating agency
must publish the guidance and all relevant documents on Regula-
tions.gov. The agency must also allow for comments on the pub-
lished documents.
Section 4—Review procedures for section 610 periodic review of
rules
When periodically reviewing rules, agencies must consider the in-
direct costs considered in the IRFA and any others arising in the
10-year period since the last review or since the publication of the
rule. If an agency fails to do the review, Advocacy will alert the
agency that the rule is no longer valid, and the agency must pub-
lish said information in the Federal Register.
