XVIII. MINORITY VIEWS
Congress passed the Regulatory Flexibility Act (RFA) in 1980 out
of concern that uniform regulations disproportionately burden
small firms.1 The Office of Advocacy (Advocacy) is responsible for
monitoring agencies’ compliance with the RFA and educates rule-
writing staff on the effect their rules would have on small busi-
nesses. Advocacy seeks to find targeted solutions that are less bur-
densome, and in Fiscal Year 2023 (FY 2023), their efforts resulted
in more than $90 million in estimated regulatory costs savings for
small businesses.2
Concerns have been raised by the Coalition for Sensible Safe-
guards and other organizations that the RFA has become a tool for
large businesses to obstruct the regulatory process. To that end,
the ‘‘Prove It Act of 2025’’ would give the biggest companies a pow-
erful new tool to use against regulations that protect our health,
environment, and safety, and cause further harm to the very small
entities it purports to help.
Cumbersome New Process Giving Powerful Trade Groups Too Much
Influence
First and foremost, the bill creates an unworkable quasi-judicial
process within Advocacy for reviewing agencies’ certification that a
regulation would not have a ‘‘significant economic effect on a sig-
nificant number of small entities (SEISNSE).’’ Unlike the original
RFA, which only allows small entities to seek judicial review, the
‘‘Prove It Act of 2025’’ ‘‘would allow an ‘‘organization representing
the interests of small entities’’ to file a petition for review with the
Chief Counsel of Advocacy. This new process would let powerful
trade associations like the U.S. Chamber of Commerce petition the
SBA to review a certification as long as the organization can claim
to represent some small entities affected by the underlying rule.
Moreover, the bill would allow these organizations to challenge the
agencies’ certifications without identifying which small businesses
they represent or how those small businesses would be harmed by
the rules they are challenging.
Once a petition is filed, the Chief Counsel would have 10 days
to determine if the petition warrants a full review. If the Chief
Counsel determines that a full review is required, the Chief Coun-
sel has 30 more days to conduct the review and publish the results.
This new process would result in additional meetings with the rep-
resentatives of small entities, agencies, Office of Information and
Regulatory Affairs (OIRA), and Advocacy. Multiple and duplicative
