Indirect Economic Effect Cost Estimates
The bill would also require agencies to include indirect economic
effects of rules in their regulatory flexibility analyses, which can be
burdensome, impracticable, and counterproductive. Under current
law, the RFA requires agencies to take into consideration the direct
impact on small entities and try to minimize the direct impact
while achieving the same goal. Indirect costs are significantly more
difficult to estimate, and agencies do not always have that informa-
tion available to them, nor do they have control over minimizing
them.
Unreviewable Discretion Granted to the Chief Counsel
In addition to creating a new process, the bill gives the Chief
Counsel unreviewable discretion to sanction the agency promul-
gating the rule by making the final rule inapplicable to small enti-
ties upon the finding that the agency failed to assist the Chief
Counsel. With 99 percent of businesses being designated as small,
the bill would allow Advocacy to essentially gut a regulation.
The Chief Counsel must also track agency completion of manda-
tory reviews of existing rules every 10 years. It requires agencies
to also conduct retrospective reviews based on the indirect costs
identified in the initial analysis. This provision doesn’t make sense
because agencies may have changed the rules significantly between
proposed and final rule stages, meaning the indirect costs identi-
fied in the proposed stage may not be applicable to the final rule,
let alone 10 years after the final rule has taken effect. To that end,
the provision is unworkable.
If the Chief Counsel finds that an agency failed to conduct a re-
quired review of a rule, the Chief Counsel could suspend operation
of the rule, meaning it wouldn’t apply to anyone or any business.
This provision creates another layer of regulatory review, which
would essentially allow Advocacy to freeze a regulation until an
agency review is conducted and then possibly reinstate the rule—
causing undue uncertainty to small businesses.
In the 118th Congress, Advocacy shared with Democratic Com-
mittee staff that small businesses need certainty in the rule-mak-
ing process and requiring small businesses to come into compliance
with a rule or regulation only to remove it from the books would
be onerous in and of itself. Advocacy further stated, ‘‘rules are inte-
grated into one another, and they have a much broader impact in
terms of who it affects, further contributing to the uncertainty in
the rulemaking process, particularly for small businesses that pro-
cure with the federal government.’’
